<li id="cite_note-217"><b><a href="#cite_ref-217" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="book" id="CITEREFLewis2006">Lewis, Hal M. (2006). <i>From Sanctuary to Boardroom: A Jewish Approach to Leadership</i>. Lanham, Md.: Rowman &amp; Littlefield. p.&#160;1. <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/0742552292" class="internal">ISBN 0-7425-5229-2</a>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=From+Sanctuary+to+Boardroom%3A+A+Jewish+Approach+to+Leadership&amp;rft.aulast=Lewis&amp;rft.aufirst=Hal+M.&amp;rft.au=Lewis%2C+Hal+M.&amp;rft.date=2006&amp;rft.pages=p.%26nbsp%3B1&amp;rft.place=Lanham%2C+Md.&amp;rft.pub=Rowman+%26+Littlefield&amp;rft.isbn=0-7425-5229-2&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Jew"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-218"><b><a href="#cite_ref-218" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="book" id="CITEREFSchwartz2001">Schwartz, Richard H. (2001). <i>Judaism and Global Survival</i>. New York: Lantern Books. p.&#160;153. <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/1930051875" class="internal">ISBN 1-930051-87-5</a>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Judaism+and+Global+Survival&amp;rft.aulast=Schwartz&amp;rft.aufirst=Richard+H.&amp;rft.au=Schwartz%2C+Richard+H.&amp;rft.date=2001&amp;rft.pages=p.%26nbsp%3B153&amp;rft.place=New+York&amp;rft.pub=Lantern+Books&amp;rft.isbn=1-930051-87-5&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Jew"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-219"><b><a href="#cite_ref-219" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="web" id="CITEREFDobbs2001">Dobbs, Stephen Mark (October 12, 2001). <a href="http://www.jewishsf.com/content/2-0-/module/displaystory/story_id/17015/edition_id/335/format/html/displaystory.html" class="external text" title="http://www.jewishsf.com/content/2-0-/module/displaystory/story_id/17015/edition_id/335/format/html/displaystory.html" rel="nofollow">"As the Nobel Prize marks centennial, Jews constitute 1/5 of laureates"</a>. <i><a href="/wiki/J." title="J.">j.</a></i><span class="printonly">. <a href="http://www.jewishsf.com/content/2-0-/module/displaystory/story_id/17015/edition_id/335/format/html/displaystory.html" class="external free" title="http://www.jewishsf.com/content/2-0-/module/displaystory/story_id/17015/edition_id/335/format/html/displaystory.html" rel="nofollow">http://www.jewishsf.com/content/2-0-/module/displaystory/story_id/17015/edition_id/335/format/html/displaystory.html</a></span><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved on January 23, 2009</span>.  "Throughout the 20th century, Jews, more so than any other minority, ethnic or cultural group, have been recipients of the Nobel Prize -- perhaps the most distinguished award for human endeavor in the six fields for which it is given. Remarkably, Jews constitute almost one-fifth of all Nobel laureates. This, in a world in which Jews number just a fraction of 1 percent of the population."</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=As+the+Nobel+Prize+marks+centennial%2C+Jews+constitute+1%2F5+of+laureates&amp;rft.atitle=%5B%5Bj.%5D%5D&amp;rft.aulast=Dobbs&amp;rft.aufirst=Stephen+Mark&amp;rft.au=Dobbs%2C+Stephen+Mark&amp;rft.date=October+12%2C+2001&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.jewishsf.com%2Fcontent%2F2-0-%2Fmodule%2Fdisplaystory%2Fstory_id%2F17015%2Fedition_id%2F335%2Fformat%2Fhtml%2Fdisplaystory.html&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Jew"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
</ol>
</div>
